title: For Sale:  swiss k31 7.5x55 rifle 350.00
postcontent:
The Swiss, Karabiner Model 31 or also known in collector slang as the Swiss Schmidt-Rubin K31 was adopted in 1933 and  stayed in service until 1958. Based on a long lineage of straight pull bolt action rifles, beginning with the Schmidt-Rubin Model 1889. Rubin designed the bullet that was combined with Schmidt's straight pull bolt rifle.  

A very accurate, detachable magazine fed rifle with a very unique straight pull bolt that allowed the soldier to quickly chamber rounds by pulling straight back on the bolt and then slamming it forward. Very revolutionary engineering in a battle rifle for the late 1800's. Because of the straight pull bolt technology the Swiss soldier did not have to raise up (exposing themselves to enemy fire) and chamber a round, like a standard turn-bolt rifle. 
this rifle is the most accurate surplus rifle i have shot.
it is in excellent shape, it has the typical scratches and dings in the stock you see in these rifles.
the bluing is in excellent shape also.
bore is mirror and crown is excellent.
if you want one of the most accurate surplus rifles there is,the swiss engineering of these rifles are amazing.

call REDACTED

postcontent:
It's an older Savage 340 chambered in .223. 
It has:
3 .223 five round mags.
Scope rings.
A 3x9 scope(not an expensive one, but a good, sturdy one)
An interchangeable barrel in .222 Remington (what the .223 was based on. A sum up of it is it shoots a bit further, and flatter than the .223, but it doesn't tumble on impact.)
2 .222 five round mags.
Seven boxes of .222 ammo.

A great, accurate, versatile rifle.
Has a few scratches from hunting, but has been cleaned and cared for well.


Note: I have no need to sell this, so unless you are local, and willing to pay much more than its worth, I will only consider trades.

title: For Sale:  scam alert- buyer beware
postcontent:
On Saturday the 26th of Jan.  I made contactvwithba seller selling 4 g.I. combat 7rd 1911 magazines.

I spoke with him a while both by text and over the phone.  He told me his name was Jason and that he lived in Matteson, Illinois.  His armslist post said the same.

We agreed on a price and agreed that first thing Monday morning I would send him a usps money order for the price plus shipping.  I followed through this morning.  While at the post office I texted him a pic of the usps money order and a photo of my food along with return address.

I realized that I had nit gotten his full name which is needed for the money order.  He then sent me a different name.  Then I realized that even though he had told me he lived in matteson illinois, he wanted me to send the money order to richton park.

When I then asked him to send me a photo I.d. he told me that it would violate his security clearence.  

This all seems too fishy to me.  He is also selling a serpa holster as well.

Beware as something is not all there with this guy

FOR SALE:  I have a brand new (never been fired) hard-to-find German Sports Guns .22 Cal replica of the famous WW II German Sturmgehr 44 (STG-44).  This is one of the finest replicas weighing and looking exactly like the original gun that was the father of all military assault rifles.  This rifle comes packed in a "period" styled wooden box, complete with markings that make it feel like you've pulled the box from some historical shelves in an old factory (see photos below).  I am also including five (5) - 25-Rd Magazines.  As indicated, it was never fired and I was keeping it as a collector's item.

RIFLE FACTS:  German Sports Guns (GSG) is in the process of releasing several exact (.22 cal firing) replicas of original (famous) WW II German Guns.  Their standards are to make the guns weigh exactly the same and look exactly the same as the originals - with no cheap shortcuts.  This STG-44 Sturmgewehr is made of solid metal and wood (weighs 10 Lbs as the original).  Even the magazines (although a plastic material) feel like metal.  Everything about this rifle smacks of originality - and wait till you hold it in your hands.  The rifle breaks down for easy cleaning (not like some .22's where you can't even take out the bolt).  Everything breaks down quickly and the bolt can be quickly removed for a thorough cleaning.  This rifle is in demand - but the few that do arrive at gun stores are quickly nabbed up, thus it's becoming an increasingly hard model to get a hold of.  YOU MUST SEE THIS RIFLE TO APPRECIATE THE BEAUTY, SOLIDITY, AND BUILD QUALITY OF THIS AWESOME REPLICA.

REASON FOR SELLING:  I'm a retired Marine and my father originally served as a German Army Officer during WW II (yes, we emigrated to the US).  Because he had often mentioned that at the end of the war he had a Sturmgewehr and loved its reliability and firepower, I've since wanted one.  When the GSG version became available, I immediately purchased two (I was very lucky).  But as the word got out, they became more difficult to acquire due to their exceptional build quality.  I'm now selling off one because having two doesn't do me any good.  I am selling this gun and magazines basically for the price I paid for everything shown.
